                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5151 Manchuria/13: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Bingham</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-10-26T14:00:00+00:00"
                            >October 26, 1937—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received October 26—9:15 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>666. Substance of the Department’s 423, October 19, 3 p.m.,<note n="49"
                        xml:id="d1066fn49">Not printed; it reported the telegraphic exchange October
                        18–19 with the Embassy in China and instructed the Embassy in the United
                        Kingdom to “take this matter up with the Foreign Office”. (893.5151
                        Manchuria/11)</note> was communicated informally to the Foreign Office on
                    October 20. The Foreign Office advises me today that instructions in
                    substantially similar terms to those of the Department were telegraphed on
                    October 22 to British representatives at Tokyo and Mukden.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bingham</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
